- 'Diabetes' and 'Hypertension' are chronic medical conditions;
- 'Average response values' are calculated from integer data types;
- 'Missing value codes' are identifiers for responses that are not applicable or missing.

- 'Most prevalent conditions' refers to conditions with the highest number of distinct patients;
- 'Longest patient participation' is calculated as the number of days between the consent date and withdrawal date;
- 'Study names' are the names of the studies in which patients participated.

- A "garden" represents a study;
- A "tree" represents a patient;
- "Fruits" represent survey responses;
- "At least five trees" means there are at least five patients in the study.

- "sown their seeds of consent" refers to patients who have provided consent (i.e., `consent_date` is not null);
- "have not yet reaped the harvest of withdrawal" refers to patients who have not withdrawn from the study (i.e., `withdrawal_date` is null);
- "thriving with the most participants" refers to the studies with the highest count of such patients.

- "beacon of patient engagement" refers to the study with the highest average number of survey responses per patient;
- "shining the brightest" is a metaphor for having the highest average number of survey responses;
- "most consistent survey responses" indicates the highest average number of responses per patient.

- "Most frequent conditions" are determined by the number of patients who have each condition;
- "More than one medical condition" implies that patients have at least two different conditions;
- "Study version" refers to the most recent version of each study.

- A "bouquet of 10 responses" refers to a count of more than 10 survey responses;
- "Blooms" refers to the names of the studies;
- "Garden of active studies" refers to the set of studies that are currently active.

- "More survey responses than the average" means the patient has a higher number of survey responses compared to the average number of survey responses across all patients;
- "More medical conditions than the average" means the patient has a higher number of medical conditions compared to the average number of medical conditions across all patients;
- "More populous study" means the study the patient is part of has more patients than the average number of patients across all studies.

- 'blossomed' refers to studies that have more than 10 unique patients;
- 'numerical in nature' refers to survey questions with the data type 'integer';
- 'participant base' refers to the number of unique patients in each study.

- "latest versions of studies and questions" refers to the versions with the most recent creation timestamps;
- "most recent responses" refers to the latest responses based on the response date;
- "integer and multiple-choice responses" indicates the data type and format of the responses.

- "still blooming" refers to studies with a status of 'active';
- "garden of souls" metaphorically refers to the patients in the study;
- "oldest garden of souls" refers to the study with the highest average patient age;
- The average age is calculated using the Julian day difference between the patients' date of birth and a reference date ('2024-03-16').

- "Trees that are still growing" refers to studies with a status of 'active';
- "Leaves" represent patients in the studies;
- "Leaves that are still green" refers to patients who have not withdrawn from the study;
- "The average age of the leaves when they first sprouted" refers to the average age of patients at the time they gave consent to participate in the study.

- Patient engagement is calculated as the total number of responses divided by the total number of patients in a study;
- The query filters out studies with zero patients to avoid division by zero;
- The query also considers missing value codes and access logs, though they are not directly used in the final selection criteria.
